comments.body: Whoa! I’ve seen red cultivars in horticultural settings, but I don’t think I’ve personally seen pink before! Very sweet :)

I saw my first pink one in the Santa Lucia mountains this past June
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/120912770
Very surprising and eyecatching!

observation.description:
Always surprising to see this species in pink

Common Yarrow (Achillea millefolium) Species name means "thousand-leaved" referring to its long, flat, and feathery fern-like leaves, which make excellent bookmarks after being pressed and dried.
Inflorescence: dense, flat-topped clusters of flowers that consist of 1) Ray florets 3–5, conspicuous; rays 2–3 mm, white, sometimes pink to red, and 2) Disc florets 10–30; corollas 2–2.5 mm, white, slightly exserted from involucres. Peak bloom time: April-June.

https://oregonflora.org/taxa/index.php?taxon=2414

Jepson eFlora https://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=678

Flora of Fort Ord: Monterey County, California, David Styer, 2019, p.28.

Plants of Monterey County: an Illustrated Field Key, 2nd edition, Matthews and Mitchell, 2015, pp.34-35.

Monterey County Wildflowers: a Field Guide, Yeager and Mitchell, 2016, p. 175.

Monterey County Wildflowers– a photographic guide https://montereywildflowers.com/asteraceae-mayweed/
